2015 Manchester Road, Wheaton, IL 60187

Don’t miss out on the PVSA March Sportsman’s show. The show is a great opportunity to get those spring shooting supplies, fishing tackle or maybe some camping gear. title: For Sale:  Cobray M11/9mm STEEL magazine
postcontent:
Found this cleaning out the closet. Sold my M11/9 years ago. Capacity 30 rnds. This thing is ugly but it works, guaranteed. If this doesn't run in your gun you can return it for a full refund! I forget what machinegun these were made for originally but it wasn't the Cobray M11/9. Cobray did modify a batch of these same type of mags by notching the top so the stock could slide inside the frame (for the SMG) and stamped them with the Cobray snake. They are the only ones I ever found made of steel that functioned flawlessly in M11/9s without modifying the grip, etc (e.g. sten conversion) The only problem with these was that they wouldn't lock into the magwell with the stock closed. Thus everyone grinds a bit off in one place on each side to allow the stock to slide closed. I did mine with a dremel and then sprayed with bbq grill paint. It's NOT pretty but it works 100%.

I see "good looking ones" selling for $60 on ar15dotcom so I'm pricing this ugly one at less than half that, $25

Text 305-8zero4-0677

title: For Sale:  Beretta Model 951
postcontent:
This pistol is in excellent condition. No rust or damage.

The Beretta M 1951 pistol, also known as M951, had been developed as a military pistol early in 1950s by Pietro Beretta Armi SpA, Italy, and had been in use by Italian, Egyptian and Israeli forces. The production of the M951 started circa 1953 and continued until 1980, when M951 had been replaced by Beretta M92. The select-fire version of the M951, known as M951R, had been developed circa 1955 and been in limited production until early 1980s, when it was replaced by Beretta M93R.
Technically, M951 is a recoil operated, locked breech pistol. The short recoiling barrel is locked to the slide by vertically tilting locking piece under the barrel (Walther P38 style locking). The trigger is of single action type, the gun features cross-bolt safety switch at the rear of the grip. The magazine release button is located at the bottom of the grip. Magazine is single stack and holds 8 rounds.
The M951R is a select-fire version of M951, that featured longer barrel, heavier slide and extended magazine that holds 10 rounds (standard 8 rounds magazines also will fit). To achieve better control over the full-auto fire, additional front grip can be installed. M951R had been used by Italian Carabineri and some anti-terror units.
Egypt produced licensed copy of the M951 under the name "Helwan".

title: For Sale:  8mm Mauser semi-auto Rare Egyptian Hakim  $550
postcontent:
The Hakim Rifle is a gas operated semi-automatic rifle. It was originally designed by Sweden and produced as the AG-42 Ljungman for the Swedish Army. The tooling and design were later sold to Egypt, and the Hakim was produced there during the 1950s and 1960s. The gas operated system is adjustable by use of a special tool on a valve at the front of the gas tube. The gas system is very simple direct impingement type whereby the flow of gas impacts directly on the front face of the bolt carrier, propelling it to the rear, which unlocks and moves the bolt as it does so. The U.S. M16 rifle utilizes a comparable system, except the flow of gas into the system is not adjustable and a self regulating device of the Johnson/Stoner type is built into the bolt carrier assembly.

Semi-auto in 8mm Mauser/ that's a huge round! It has a 10 round box magazine. Sell face to face only.  
Price is $550.  REDACTED
